    <p>WALLACE: Giorgio Rizzoni is with the Center for Automotive Research in Columbus.</p>
    <p>RIZZONI: Every two or three months or so, there is an announcement of company X is reopening manufacturing plant A in Michigan or in Ohio.</p>
    <p>WALLACE: It's simple math, really: production costs are going up in China and down here. That's in part because U.S. workers are more productive and because auto industry wages have dropped since the recession. But Ohio's still playing catch-up. In the last decade the Dayton area alone lost 40 thousand manufacturing jobs. So there are workers to spare here and a lot of nostalgia for building cars.</p>
